Happy Friday and welcome back to our 88th Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Another jammed packed week for the optimists. I am going to combine a coupl=
e of this week=E2=80=99s stories to paint a future for you. The year is 204=
4 =E2=80=94 synthetic natural gas pulled from our skies cleanly and cheaply=
 powers unimaginably powerful quantum computing centers, which are solving =
complex drug discovery problems to produce tenth generation GLP-1s that can=
 basically treat any disease.=20
Sounds like SciFi, right? Answer that after reading this week=E2=80=99s Wee=
kly Dose.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) How Microsoft and Quantinuum achieved reliable quantum computing [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/173202d1-9bb1-4527-95c3-1fa52bbaddbe?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Microsoft
By applying an innovative qubit-virtualization system to ion-trap hardware,=
 Microsoft and Quantinuum were able to create four highly reliable logical =
qubits from only 30 physical qubits, while demonstrating an 800x improvemen=
t in error rate.
Microsoft announced a significant advancement in quantum computing, achievi=
ng an 800x improvement in the logical error rate of qubits. Reducing the er=
ror rate in quantum computing is crucial because it makes quantum computers=
 more accurate and reliable, allowing them to perform complex calculations =
without mistakes. Reducing the error rate is the central challenge in getti=
ng useful, and ultimately commercializable, quantum computing.
Microsoft's integrated its qubit-virtualization system with Quantinuum's ha=
rdware, resulting in highly reliable logical qubits created from a smaller =
number of physical qubits. The enhanced reliability, demonstrated through s=
uccessful error diagnostics and corrections, meets critical criteria for re=
liable quantum computing and marks a transition towards fault-tolerant quan=
tum computers. Using the combined techniques =E2=80=94 Microsoft=E2=80=99s =
visualization scheme and Quantinuum=E2=80=99s hardware =E2=80=94 the resear=
chers were able to run thousands of experiments with virtually no errors. B=
oom.
Quantum is one of those fields where the work is so complex that its someti=
me hard to grok its importance. But imagine a world in which we have comput=
ers that are millions to billions of times more powerful than the supercomp=
uters we have today. And imagine aiming those computers towards really any =
computational challenge =E2=80=94 drug discovery, material science, cryptog=
raphy, or, say, generative AI. If and when we crack this, the world is goin=
g to be a much different =E2=80=94 and better =E2=80=94 place.=20
(2) Terraform Industries converts electricity and air into synthetic natura=
l gas for the first time [ https://substack.com/redirect/c816180a-8cab-40bd=
-bfc4-f0639e8d215d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU ]
Aria Alamalhodaei for Tech Crunch
Instead of reducing humanity=E2=80=99s dependence on hydrocarbons =E2=80=94=
 which is impossible or undesirable or both, depending on who you ask =E2=
=80=94 Terraform Industries [ https://substack.com/redirect/71f0670f-8536-4=
893-a355-513c0c08dd74?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=99 solution is to produce this resource, using electr=
icity and air, via a system it calls the Terraformer. Today, the startup is=
 announcing that it has commissioned a demonstrator Terraformer and produce=
d synthetic natural gas for the first time.
Last week, we profiled Terraform=E2=80=99s founder Casey Handmer and, as if=
 on cue, his company announced that it=E2=80=99s produced synthetic natural=
 gas for the first time. The company=E2=80=99s Terraformer is designed to c=
reate synthetic natural gas using electricity and air, providing a renewabl=
e alternative to traditional hydrocarbons. The machine is made up of three =
parts:
Electrolyzer: Uses solar power to split water into hydrogen and oxygen, ess=
entially creating hydrogen gas.
Direct Air Capture: Extracts carbon dioxide (CO2) from the air, providing t=
he carbon needed to form natural gas.
Chemical Reactor: The hydrogen from the electrolyzer and the CO2 from the a=
ir capture system are combined in this reactor, producing synthetic natural=
 gas.
And voil=C3=A0, we have synthetic natural gas pulled from sunlight and air.=
 The team has a long way to go in scaling up its systems and getting costs =
down, but it=E2=80=99s a major step step for them towards generating abunda=
nt, clean energy pulled directly from the skies.
(3) Trial of Lixisenatide in Early Parkinson=E2=80=99s Disease [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/76c35b86-0c2f-4388-9e65-833909e25170?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From the New England Journal of Medicine
Lixisenatide, a glucagon-like peptide-1 receptor agonist used for the treat=
ment of diabetes, has shown neuroprotective properties in a mouse model of =
Parkinson=E2=80=99s disease.
Man, these GLP-1s are something else, huh? Lose weight, curb cravings, mana=
ge diabetes, reduce heart disease=E2=80=A6and now, according to new researc=
h published this week, slow Parkinson=E2=80=99s.
Over a year long study, the group taking lixisenatide showed slight improve=
ment (=E2=88=920.04 points change), whereas the placebo group worsened (3.0=
4 points increase) on tests designed to measure motor disability changes. T=
hat=E2=80=99s a pretty big deal! Parkinson=E2=80=99s is the second most pre=
valent neurodegenerative disease in the U.S. behind Alzheimer=E2=80=99s and=
 over half a million people have been diagnosed with it. A drug that can sl=
ow and delay the onset of Parkinson=E2=80=99s symptoms should have a major =
quality of life impact for those patients.
GLP-1s, like lixisenatide, may be effective in treating Parkinson's and oth=
er neurodegenerative diseases by addressing insulin resistance in the brain=
 and interacting with neuronal proteins, potentially protecting neurons and=
 slowing disease progression. Just another day at the office for GLP-1s!
(4) Sleeping for One Week on a Temperature-Controlled Mattress Cover Improv=
es Sleep and Cardiovascular Recovery [ https://substack.com/redirect/fd9afc=
eb-239a-42d9-a6eb-b40656e91ec3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjml=
XXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Eight Sleep
This is not a sponsored placement, but given that the Not Boring community =
probably has a higher density of Eight Sleep users than any other group in =
the world, we thought we=E2=80=99d share the company=E2=80=99s latest findi=
ngs on sleep improvement.
The study by Eight Sleep demonstrated that using the Pod improved sleep qua=
lity, increased deep, light, and REM sleep stages, and enhanced cardiovascu=
lar recovery, evidenced by a decrease in heart rate and an increase in hear=
t rate variability. There was a about a ~20% increase in deep and light sle=
ep while the Pod was on. Cardiovascular recovery was also positively impact=
ed by the Pod, with a 2% decrease in average heart rate and a 7% increase i=
n heart rate variability.
To be honest, it=E2=80=99s sometimes hard tough to trust these company-back=
ed scientific studies that are not part of a formal FDA process, even when =
they=E2=80=99re peer-reviewed. But, at face value, the results confirm what=
 basically any Eight Sleep customer will happily chat your ear off about. T=
he Pod works! This looks like a case where the actual data backs up the ane=
cdata.
(5) Kalshi Onboards Its First Dedicated Institutional Market Maker [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/66ec2934-8ca9-48ee-acb8-91865a0f49d6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Kalshi, the first federally regulated exchange dedicated to trading on even=
t outcomes, announced today their first dedicated institutional market mark=
er in the ecosystem, Susquehanna Government Products, LLLP, a member of the=
 Susquehanna International Group of Companies (=E2=80=9CSIG=E2=80=9D).
Kalshi, the prediction market on which you can pretty much wager on any lar=
ge event, announced SIG as its (and the ecosystem at large=E2=80=99s) first=
 dedicated market maker. This is a big deal for Kalshi, not only because SI=
G lends some level of credibility, but also because it provides much needed=
 liquidity and price stability for what can be pretty volatile markets. The=
 role of the market maker is to ensure that there is always a counterparty =
available for traders wanting to enter or exit positions. This is particula=
rly important for nascent prediction markets like Kalshi where liquidity ca=
n otherwise be scarce.
Now a skeptic may look at Kalshi and label it as just another way for gambl=
ers to get their fix on a new set of alternative contracts, but prediction =
markets =E2=80=94 be it the stock market or Kalshi =E2=80=94 generally lead=
 to positive outcomes for society. Prediction markets lead to better inform=
ation aggregation and discovery, more efficient risk management, more respo=
nsive governance, amongst other things.=20
If you believe David Deutsch=E2=80=99s Principle of Optimism =E2=80=94 =E2=
=80=9CAll evils are caused by insufficient knowledge.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 th=
en prediction markets that harness and publish collective knowledge are a v=
ery optimistic thing indeed.=20
I have yet to find a more reliable and legible outcome indicator than Kalsh=
i =E2=80=94 on everything from interest rates and political outcomes to Tel=
sa production volumes and Taylor Swift album predictions.
No sports yet on Kalshi =E2=80=94 I am sure that will change eventually =E2=
=80=94 but until then, you=E2=80=99ll have to download the sports book app =
of your choice to place your Caitlin Clark prop bets this weekend.
Bonus: Packy here, popping in to tell you about something very fun happenin=
g on the internet. There=E2=80=99s a guy in Kenya named Richard Opany [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/65f97937-fd1b-4bc8-b54b-5e38823b7f4d?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] who tweeted =E2=
=80=9C@worldcoin thanks=E2=80=9D with a picture of a goat on April 1st. He =
put the @worldcoin first, the ultimate visibility killer on twitter, just w=
anted to say thanks.=20
Somehow, people found the tweet, realized that he meant that he used the Wo=
rldcoin he received for setting up his account to buy a goat, and asked how=
 much a goat cost [ https://substack.com/redirect/12ba14b8-4db6-4e87-8b1c-8=
486de675458?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]. He said $50. Leighton Cusack [ https://substack.com/redirect/40e9c6c=
9-8bf0-4cbe-8507-6abb75d95775?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] asked for his wallet address, sent him $100, and as=
ked him to name the two goats =E2=80=9Chigher=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cenjoy/b=
ased.=E2=80=9D He did.=20
Now lots of people are sending Richard $50 or $100 in crypto and asking him=
 to name goats for them. Based on a quick scan [ https://substack.com/redir=
ect/716c5540-784c-49eb-b061-335af3d0826e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_=
ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], it looks like he=E2=80=99s received tho=
usands of dollars=E2=80=99, or dozens of goats=E2=80=99, worth of crypto. S=
omeone sent him $1,850 worth of the Farcaster coin $DEGEN [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/559bc87c-4d51-41b6-9e90-514f825340c9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. There=E2=80=99s even an NFT =
of the goat named Higher that=E2=80=99s raised .82 ETH [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/49c957bc-c4d4-4bfc-8605-693cbb081fdc?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] ($2,700), half of which is going=
 to Richard to buy more goats, half of which is going to the treasury of th=
e memecoin collective Higher that the goat is named after.=20
It=E2=80=99s all very dumb, and very fun, and very wholesome. The memecoin =
gets marketing, Richard gets goats, and everyone gets a little joy. I love =
the internet. =20
Double Bonus: Speaking of Africa=E2=80=A6 Russ Cook (@hardestgeezer [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/11ded368-cf79-4002-9052-ed7af79f820c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]) is completing his =
nearly year-long run of the entire continent of Africa this weekend. This h=
as been an amazing journey to follow and a reminder that we humans can (and=
 should) accomplish incredibly hard things.
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox early next week.
Thanks for reading,
Packy + Dan

